{"type":"click","text":"B\n    \n      Unified Manager (Top-Down)\n      A single TerrainWeatherManager orchestrates everything — terrain, weather, growth, effects.\n      \n        TerrainWeatherManager\n          ├── manages TerrainCellGrid\n          ├── spawns/moves WeatherFronts\n          ├── runs growth ticks\n          ├── applies character effects\n          └── handles footstep lookups\n      \n      \n        Pros\n          Fewer files — everything in one place\n          Simple to understand initially\n        \n        Cons\n          God-class risk — one manager doing 5 jobs\n          Violates SRP from your project rules\n          Hard to test individual concerns\n          Adding new terrain types or effects means modifying the manager\n          Offline simulation tightly coupled to runtime logic","choice":"b","id":null,"timestamp":1775124253990}
{"type":"click","text":"A\n    \n      Layered Architecture (Bottom-Up)\n      Each concern is a standalone system. They communicate via events — minimal coupling.\n      \n        Layer 5 — Effects\n          FootstepAudioResolver · CharacterTerrainEffects (speed/damage/slip)\n        ↑ reads terrain state\n        Layer 4 — Growth\n          VegetationGrowthSystem (wild) · CropSystem (plowed)\n        ↑ reads moisture + fertility\n        Layer 3 — Weather ↔ Terrain\n          TerrainWeatherProcessor (WeatherFront passes over cells → updates moisture, temp)\n        ↑ WeatherFront position + cell grid\n        Layer 2 — Weather Movement\n          WeatherFront (GameObject) · GlobalWindController · BiomeRegion (bounds + spawn rules)\n        ↑ driven by global wind + local wind\n        Layer 1 — Terrain Foundation\n          TerrainType (enum/SO) · TerrainCellGrid · TerrainZone (base type)\n      \n      \n        Pros\n          Each layer can be built and tested independently\n          Easy to add new terrain types or weather types without touching other layers\n          MacroSimulator only needs Layer 1 + math formulas — no GameObjects\n          Follows your existing SOLID patterns\n          Footstep audio is just a consumer — completely decoupled from weather\n        \n        Cons\n          More files/classes upfront\n          Event wiring between layers needs careful setup\n        \n      \n      \n        Recommended — Matches your project's architecture philosophy. Each system has one job. Easy to implement incrementally (Layer 1 first, then 2, etc.)","choice":"a","id":null,"timestamp":1775124300724}
{"type":"click","text":"A\n    \n      Layered Architecture (Bottom-Up)\n      Each concern is a standalone system. They communicate via events — minimal coupling.\n      \n        Layer 5 — Effects\n          FootstepAudioResolver · CharacterTerrainEffects (speed/damage/slip)\n        ↑ reads terrain state\n        Layer 4 — Growth\n          VegetationGrowthSystem (wild) · CropSystem (plowed)\n        ↑ reads moisture + fertility\n        Layer 3 — Weather ↔ Terrain\n          TerrainWeatherProcessor (WeatherFront passes over cells → updates moisture, temp)\n        ↑ WeatherFront position + cell grid\n        Layer 2 — Weather Movement\n          WeatherFront (GameObject) · GlobalWindController · BiomeRegion (bounds + spawn rules)\n        ↑ driven by global wind + local wind\n        Layer 1 — Terrain Foundation\n          TerrainType (enum/SO) · TerrainCellGrid · TerrainZone (base type)\n      \n      \n        Pros\n          Each layer can be built and tested independently\n          Easy to add new terrain types or weather types without touching other layers\n          MacroSimulator only needs Layer 1 + math formulas — no GameObjects\n          Follows your existing SOLID patterns\n          Footstep audio is just a consumer — completely decoupled from weather\n        \n        Cons\n          More files/classes upfront\n          Event wiring between layers needs careful setup\n        \n      \n      \n        Recommended — Matches your project's architecture philosophy. Each system has one job. Easy to implement incrementally (Layer 1 first, then 2, etc.)","choice":"a","id":null,"timestamp":1775124357788}
